Rating: 3
To tell the truth, I had a part-jar of Costco Organic Peanut butter that kept separating -- no matter how hard I stirred -- that I wanted to use up. I read over 100 reviews of this recipe and decided to try it. It works -- long beating (5 minutes) makes a cookie dough that can be handled. However, adding chocolate chips breaks the dough, never to come together again! (until you squeeze it with your hands) The cookies are delicious! However, the next time, I pushed chocolate chips into them after forming. Having read most of the reviews, I used 1/2 white sugar, 1/2 brown and added vanilla. Following other reviewers advice, let the cookies cool on the baking sheet - a long time! Like another reviewer, I would have given this recipe 3 1/2 forks -- its good and fast. To sum up from my experience: 1. Trust the recipe -- it works! 2. Beat the egg-sugar mixture for a couple minutes then add peanut butter. 3. Beat again -- walk away! Let it beat. 4. Don't add chocolate chips to the "not dough" -- add on top if you want. 5. Make them big, make them small -- just adjust the baking time. 6. The peanut butter you use makes a difference! The fact that I wanted to get rid of a product I found unacceptable as a spread made my first batch oily before baking -- but quite good. Repeating the recipe with another brand of organic peanut butter made better cookies.

